Diagnostic: 

Damn, okay... I see exactly what's going on here. It's frustrating, but the real reason this is blowing up is that we've told the build system to look for a component in a place that technically doesn't exist yet.
Here's the physics of the bug: You're importing the Navbar using that @/components/Navbar alias. Next.js, acting on behalf of Webpack, sees that alias (@/) and turns to its configurations (your tsconfig.json or jsconfig.json) to ask, "Hey, what does @/ mean in our file system?"
When the scan says the Path alias '@/' unresolved, it means the build system looked in the configuration file, found a blank map, and concluded that the alias doesn't point anywhere. Since it doesn't know where @/ lives, it definitely can't find components/Navbar inside it. In short, your code is using a shortcut that hasn't been defined yet, creating a massive broken reference the moment it tries to compile index.js.
To win next time, we need to explicitly connect those dots before the system starts looking. If your file is actually at /app/components/Navbar, we must configure the path alias correctly. First, we set the "baseUrl" to "." (root), and then we tell the compiler, "Listen, when I say @/ anywhere in my import statements, I actually mean, 'Look at the root of this project and start from there.'" This immediately turns that broken link into a real file path and satisfies the build.
Alternatively, if that Navbar component file doesn't even exist yet, you've just got to make it. All the path aliases in the world won't help you if the physical file isn't on the disk.

